Folder 1. Cerastium latifolium [G]. i. Cites Ray's Syn. 349. ii. "Cerastium alpinum. This was gathered upon Snowdon at the top of the highest Rock call'd Clogwyn y Garnedh. June" [JL]. iii. "Top of Snowdon" [JL]. iv. "Dr. Solander affirms this to be the true Cerastium alpinum. I had it from Snowdon. He found it at Terra del Fuego & named it C. hirtum with a mark of Dubitation, but now thinks them both one" [JL].
Folder 2. Cerastium alpinum [TA]; Cerastium latifolium [G]. i. "Clogwyn dû" [JL]. ii. "Cerast: alpin: Ben Lomond" [JL].

Folder 1. Cerastium alpinum [G]. i. "Anglesey. Cerastium alpinum. Q: an Var: aut nova species? Fig: Cerast: alp: non quadrat: Flor: Dan: The Fig: in the fl. Dan: of Cerast: alpinum agrees with this, only taller & more branched, bearing 6 flowers, capsulis oblongis. In the Fl. Lapponic: Lin: says this Plant commonly produced 1 or 2 flowers when wild" [JL]. ii. "Cerastium alpinum? Newfoundland. The Flor: Dan: agrees well with the tall one. I believe the others to be nothing but Varieties" [JL]. [Only two specimens in folder; on left C. arcticum, probably the plant from Anglesey; on right C. arvense, maybe the specimen from Newfoundland collected by Joseph Banks.]

Folder 2. Cerastium uniflorum [TA]; Cerastium alpinum? [G]. i. "Cerastium latifolium? This was gathered on Mount Snowdon by the Sides of the Rivulets to the North of Wyddfa by the Revd Mr Williams. June & July" [JL].

Folder 1. Euphorbia exigua [G]. i. "I found this plant, 1773, in our Cornfields, and supposed it to be only a variety of the exigua. I am still of the same opinion. It agrees indeed pretty well with the Tishy-malus Segetum longifolius. Cat. Cant. App & Rall Syn. p.312, since it is there described as Esulae exiguae Tragi persimilis, sed major; wch last circumstance may easily be accounted for; *because of the Umbella quinquefida in the one & trifida in the other. The Segetalis in Ray and the Segetalis in Linnaeus are certainly two very different Plants; and I should be glad to know, and I wish it may be in your power to inform me, whether those Specimens, wch Mr. Lyons found near Triplow, be at all different from this Specimen—another circumstance also makes me conclude that it is only a variety of the exigua; because found in company wth it, and am inclined to think that it never will be found anywhere else. I gathered more of it at the same Time; but have either mislaid or shuffled it away. But if I should find the same variety again, I will endeavour to collect the Seed of it, and try what it will do in my Garden. *Supposing all other circumstances equal, the quinquefida must be to the trifida in Magnitude in the Proportion of 5 to 3, wch wants only one third part of being twice as big" [B]. ii. "Euphorbia segetalis of D. Lyons, not of Lin: It seems to be only a Variety of Euphorb: exigua Lin: In Cornfields in Norfolk, Mr. Bryant. I compared this with Lyon's own Specimen, now in the possession of Mr. Banks" [JL].

Sheet 1. Galeopsis eboracensis [TA]; G. hirta [G]. i. Cites Ray's Syn. 242. ii. "Yellow-flower'd field Ironwort. July. This Plant grows wild in the West Riding of Yorkshire, about Wakefield, Darfield, Sheffield & c. among Corn plentifully. It belongs to Linnaeus's Genus of Galeopsis, the lower Lip of the flower having the two elevated hollow Dents, which are the Characters of that Genus, but it is taken no Notice of by that Author under that Genus or any other. Hudson falsely calls it Betonica hirta. The Plant is about a foot or eighteen Inches high, & branched; the flowers have long Tubes, are of a light yellow Colour almost white, with the inside of the lower lip mark'd with a deeper yellow. It differs from the Galeopsis Tetrahit in having no gouty Swellings at the Joints, nor long Hairs upon the Leaves & Stalks, nor acutely serrated, nor long weak Aristae to the Calyces" [JL]. iii. "Prob. Galeopsis ochraleuca or Downy Hemp Nettle" [?].

N° 1 I begged of M' Pitchford, that I might see what he understood by the Mentha hirsuta Huds., but he can assign no other Reason for it, than that the Stamina are Shorter than the Calyx. His Specimen is the same w' th" [on reverse:] "N° 2, where they are longer" [B]. iii. "this mint from Dr H: [probably Dr Hope] was it found in Scotland?" [JL].

In N°s 1,2,3, w' ch are evidently the same Plant, you find all the Marks w' ch constitute the Differences between the arvensis, aquatica, & hirsuta, Huds. the Floribus capitatis therefore is not to be depended upon, no more than the length of the Stamina—and indeed I have found some Instances where the Floribus capitatis & verticillatis have been produced on different Branches from one and the same Root" [B].

Linum perenne [TA]. i. Cites Ray's Syn. 362. ii. "Perennial blue Flax. July. This Plant is found on the Banks of barren Pastures in several Places, as on Gogmagog Hills in Cambridgeshire, on the Balks of Corn-fields about Bernak Heath in Northamptonshire, & plentifully in the Isle of Shepey in Kent, & c." [JL].

Folder 1. Linum angustifolium [G]. i. Cites Ray's Syn. 362. ii. "Narrow-leav'd wild Flax. July. This is a rare English Plant but grows plentifully in the Pastures bythe Seaside about St. Ives & Truro in Cornwall. It has been found likewise in similar Places near the Sea Coast in Sussex & Kent" [JL]; "The flowers of this Sp: are not 1/2 so large as those of the Perenne, nor so deep a Blue" [TA].

This Plant comes out of my Garden, raised from Seed of your Sending-But is seems to me to be the 'Linum sylvestre caeruleum perenne procumbens, flore & capitulo minore' - R. Syn. No. 4. p. 362 w. Huds. makes a Variety of the perenne β - The Linum tenuifolium Huds. is the variety ξ Linnaeus" [B]; "This is certainly the Lin: of Ray p. 362 no. 5 but whether L. tenuif: Lin. Quiere" [JL].

This is said to be found in Haselwood near S' Walter Vavasor's Park in Yorkshire. These specimens came, the one from Sweden, the other from Newfoundland. I have found it also in Scotland in shady old Beech Woods. N.B. The Antherae in this Species stand out of the Corolla, and the Stigma is lengthened beyond the Stamina" [JL]. iii. The only material Difference between this Species & the Pyr: minor consists in the Extrusion of the Stamina & Style. The Flowers lean also to one side of the Stalk, & the Leaves are more acute" [JL]. Folder 1. Pyrola minor [G]. i. Cites Ray's Syn. 363. ii. "Common Winter-Green, June & July. I have found this in many Places in England, as in Common Wood two Miles from Halifax in Yorkshire; in a Wood half a Mile from Nettlebed call'd Sounded in Oxfordshire; In a Wood call'd Lambridge near S' Thos Stapleton's about three Miles from Henley [Grey's Court], & in many Places in Mungewell Woods not far from the same Place. I have found it likewise in Buckinghamshire in the Parish of Medenham between Henley & Great Marlow, in the Beach-Woods by the Road's Side" [JL]. Folder 2. Pyrola rotundifolia??? [TA]. i. "Pyrola minor Lin: From the Woods near Little-Loch-Broom in Ross-shire. Scotland. 1772" [JL]. Folder 4. Pyrola minor [TA].

Folder 1. Alchemilla vulgaris [TA], Flora Scotica ed. 1, 120 (1777). i. "Ladies Mantle. June & July. This smooth Kind of Ladies Mantle is much less common in England than the little pubescent one. I never saw it anywhere but at Longsledale [Long Sleddale, a valley a few miles northwest of Kendal] in Westmoreland. I imagine this to be the most frequent in Sweden as Linnaeus has given it the Epithet of vulgaris. It retains its Smoothness when planted in a Garden for many Years, but this is hardly to be allow'd as a true specific Mark to difference it from the other" [JL].

folders.description: Salix vitellina [TA]. i. "Salix vitellina. mas. In the Osier Bed by Mr. Biggs's Mill [near Cowley, Middlesex]. April 29th. 1777. a cold Season. It is diandrous" [JL].

Folder 1. Salix nova [TA]; S. arbuscula [G]. i. "These seem to be the original specimens of what Mr. Lightfoot described for Salix myrsinites (no such thing. T.A.) (he having wrote Arbuscula on the enclosed ticket by mistake) see Flora Scotica. This is not however the true myrsinites, which is what he had from Glen-co (see other paper) but rather a new species, which Linnaeus himself seems by his herbarium to have confounded with myrisinites. J.E. Smith" [JES]. ii. "Ex Craigvore Scotland. Species nova. T.A." [TA].

Folder 2. Salix nova [TA]; S. arbuscula [G]. i. "I take this to be a new species, distinguishable by its oval capsules. J.E. Smith" [JES]; "or it may be the same with Lightfoot's myrsinites" [JES]; "Impossible, the above right. T.A." [TA].

Folder 3. Salix myrtilloides and S. myrsinotes [G]. i. "Salix myrsinotes. Bulls. [Bulstrode Park]" [JL]. ii. "Salix myrsinotes? at Bullstrode from Scotland at first. Ayton calls it myrtilloides" [JL].
Folder 4. Salix arbuscula [TA]; S. myrsinotes [G]. i. "S. myrsinotes seu Arbuscula. Bullstrode. from Scotland" [JL].

Folder 5. Salix phylicifolia [G]. i. "Salix phylicifolia Herb: Linn. ex Finlarig Scotland. J.E. Smith" [TA]. ii. "N° 149. Ben-challum Oc't 19th" [Stuart]; "This comes very near to S. glauca but thro' a Lens the Leaves appear not intire but serrated" [JL]. iii. "I think these S. phylicifolia. J.E. Smith" [JES]. [Top left specimen not S. arbuscula.]
Folder 1. Salix aurita [G]. i. "Salix aurita near Iver Heath, by the Orchis field" [JL].

Folder 2. Salix aurita [G]. i. "This is exactly S. aurita. H. Linn. - 369. Fl. Lapp." [JES]. ii. "N° 71. Finlarig. May 11th" [Stuart]; "S. alba?" [JL]. iii. "N° 136. Achlyne May 1st and Finlarig May 11th" [Stuart]. iv. "N° 152. Glenlochy. May 25th" [Stuart].
Folder 3. Salix aurita [TA]. i. "The true S. aurita. male. Cumberland" [JL]; [in pencil:] "H. Linn." [? JES]. ii. "S. aurita. female, more grown. Cumberland" [JL].

Folder 4. Salix aurita? [G]. i. "Salix Aurita. Fl. Sc. 602. In a more advance State, w'th Small roundish stipula" [B]; "Mr. Bryant" [JL]. ii. "Salix aurita. Fl. Sc. 602" [B]; "Mr. Bryant" [JL]. iii. "Salix cinerea? Sp. Pl. 1449" [B]; "Mr. Bryant" [JL]. [Specimen on left side is S. cinerea.]

Folder 5. Salix aurita? [TA]. i. "Salix aurita. Bullstrode Stock Ground" [JL]. ii. "N° 301 Achmora. June 7th" [Stuart]. iii. "Salix aurita?" [JL]. [Two specimens on left are S. cinerea subsp. oleifolia Macreight.]
Folder 1. Salix caprea [G]. i. "S. Caprea fem. Gulch well" [JL]. [Specimen on left is S. cinerea subsp. oleifolia Macreight.]
Folder 2. Salix caprea [G].
Folder 1. Salix cinerea [TA]. i. "Salix cinerea Linn. Flora Suecica" [JES]. ii. "Cumberland" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix cinerea [TA]. i. "S. cinerea. H. Linn." [JES].

Folder 3. salix capreae, Var., Lightfoot [G]. i. "N° 70. Comrie. May 29th" [Stuart]; "Caprea?" [JL]. ii. "Cumberland. S. aurita var. of Capreae s. glauca?" [JL]. iii. "My Var: of S. Caprea near Chertsey. I think it a distinct species" [JL].
Folder 1. Salix amygdalina [TA]; S. fragilis [G].

species.speciesName: Salix fragilis var. russelliana (Sm.) Koch, Flora Europaea 1: 45 (1964)

folders.description: Folder 1. Salix fragilis [G]. i. "I take this to be Salix amygdalina. Lalam [now spelled Laleham] near Staines" [JL].
Folder 1. Salix herbacea [JL]. i. Cites Ray's Syn. 448. ii. "Herbaceous Willow. June. On the Sides of Mount Snowdon in Carnarvonshire" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix herbacea [G]. i. "That without Flowers on Snowdon. The greater var. of Salix herbacea" [JL]. ii. "That in flower S. herbaceae var. Rum & Arran" [JL].
Folder 1. Salix lappona [TA]. i. "Salix Lappon: Bulls. [Bulstrode Park]" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix arenaria [TA]; S. lapponum? [G]. i. "N° 150. Creg- chaillech. Sep' 3" [Stuart]; "My S. Lapponum but very like the S. arenaria of Haller—hist. p. 195 f. 14" [JL].
Folder 1. Salix myrsinities [TA]. i. "Ex Glenco, Scotland" [TA].
Folder 2. Salix myrsinities? [G]. i. "N° 140. Glenlochy. May 25th" [Stuart]; "S. myrsinities? or Arbus- cula? See my other Specimens describ'd" [JL].
Folder 1. Salix pentandria [TA]. i. "S. 5 - and. It grows wild almost the whole Way between Moffat & the Lead Hills. It grows also in the Meadow a Publick Walk at Edinburgh. Yald: [Yalden]" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix pentandra [G]. i. "N° 260" [Stuart]; "S. pentandra? Scotland" [JL]. [Specimen in top right corner is near S. nigricans Sm.] [See also under S. triandra L. Folder 2.]
Folder 1. Salix Helix [G], Flora Scotica ed. 1, 597 (1777). i. "S. Helix. right. Scotland" [JL]. ii. "Salix Helix near Oxford" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix Helix [G]. i. "S. Helix mas. Mr. Bogg's's [sic]... [illegible]" [JL].

Folder 3. Salix Helix [TA]. i. "Sa- lix Helix. Gulch Well. right. May- 74" [JL]. ii. "This Salix in the Lane going from Colnbrook to Staines, on the left. June. var. of Helix" [JL]. iii. "N° 139. Laggan near Comrie. June 1st" [Stuart]. iv. "N° 73. Curr near Comrie. June 1" [Stuart]; "S. Helix" [JL].
Folder 4. Salix purpurea? [TA]; S. Helix [G].
Folder 1. Salix repens [TA]. i. "Hounslow H: [Hounslow Heath]" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix repens [G]. i. "Salix repens? of Mr. Yalden" [JL].
Folder 3. Salix repens [G].

Folder 4. Salix fusca [TA]. i. [Written on a capsule containing the specimen:] "N° 24. Stuart. Scotl- d Salix repens s. fusca. the female" [JL]. ii. "According to the Fig: quoted by Lin: this is his Salix repens; but it remains very doubtful, whether or not it be S: fusca or repens. See for the S: repens on Put- ney Heath" [JL].
Salix arenaria [G].
Salix reticulata [TA]. i. "N° 145" [Stuart]. ii. "N° 147. Mal-gyrdy - Aug." [Stuart]. iii. "N° 18. Mal-gyrdy & Mal-grea" [Stuart]; "Salix reticulata" [JL]. [Only one specimen in folder.]
Salix alba? [TA].
Salix rubra [G]. i. "S. viminalis a Variety smooth underneath. Harefield [Middlesex]" [JL].

Salix lanata [TA]. i. "N° 137. Finlarig May 11th" [Stuart]; "S. 1641. Haller an var. S. Lanata Lin: a var. Haller 1651. This is very like Haller's S. arenaria p. 195. t. 14: but I made it S. lanata"[Catalogue] 175 [JL]. [Specimen is type of S. sphace- lata Sm.]
Folder 1. Salix fragilis [TA]; S. amygdaloides Huds. [G]; S. triandra Huds.? [G]. i. "I take this to be S. fragilis rather than S. hastata. Laleam [Laleham near Staines]" [JL].
Folder 2. Salix pentandra [G]. i. "S. pentandra between Moffat & the Lead Hills plentifully. Yalden" [JL].

Folder 3. Salix triandra foemina [TA]. i. "Salix triandra Lin. In an Osier Holt on the left Hand of the Road going to Bigg's Mill from Cowley. It flower'd April 29th. 1777, a cold Season. A shrub 12 feet high. The young Leaves of a narrow lanceolate form, smooth on both sides, & at first intire on the Edges, except those near the Summit w'ch are serrated. When full grown they generally become all serrated. Flowers & Leaves from the same Gem. Catkin an Inch long" [JL]. [Specimen incomplete, possibly S. triandra].
Folder 1. Salix viminalis [G].
Folder 2. Salix viminalis [TA]. [Inadequate specimen, possibly S. viminalis].
